Graph Transformer Neural Integrator (GraphTNI): Error-Controlled Surrogate Approximation for N-Body Gravitational Systems

Author: Ouadi Maakoul
Affiliation: Independent Researcher
Date: April 2026

---

Abstract

We develop a rigorous theoretical framework for accelerating gravitational N-body simulations using a transformer-based surrogate integrator. We define the Graph Transformer Neural Integrator (GraphTNI), a permutation-equivariant transformer architecture that directly approximates the Hamiltonian flow map $\Phi_h$ over a timestep $h$. The central contribution is a global error bound (Theorem 2) for a hybrid predictor-corrector scheme, proving that periodic synchronization with a symplectic reference solver every $C$ steps transforms exponential error growth from the base timestep $h$ into growth governed by the correction interval $C h$. Under the assumption that GraphTNI is trained on trajectories generated by a symplectic integrator, we prove that its dynamics are $C^1$-close to a symplectic map, implying the existence of an approximate shadow Hamiltonian and $\mathcal{O}(t)$ energy drift over long timescales (Proposition 1). We derive an approximation rate (Theorem 5) establishing that for Hölder-smooth flows, the local surrogate error satisfies $\epsilon_{\text{LLM}} = \mathcal{O}(d_{\text{model}}^{-s/D} + L^{-s/D})$, and we provide a rigorous analysis of sparse attention approximation error for long-range kernels (Theorem 4). This work establishes a unified mathematical foundation for error-controlled deployment of transformer-based surrogates in chaotic Hamiltonian systems.

