3.2 Hybrid Integrators and Adaptive Time-Stepping

Saz Ulibarrena et al. (2024) proposed a hybrid integrator that uses a neural network to approximate the dynamics and falls back to a numerical solver when the prediction is inaccurate. Their method achieves speedups for $N \gtrsim 70$ without significant energy error. However, the choice of when to correct is based on heuristics rather than a rigorous error bound.

More recently, Saz Ulibarrena and Portegies Zwart (2025) used reinforcement learning to adapt the time-step size in the chaotic three-body problem, automatically selecting optimal steps that balance accuracy and speed. Our Theorem 2 provides the missing theoretical justification: the optimal correction interval $C_{\text{opt}}$ derived in Eq. (13) aligns with the learned policy's behavior of reducing steps in high-curvature regions.

3.3 Scalable Graph Networks for Particle Simulations

Martinkus et al. (2021) introduced a hierarchical graph network that transforms a fully-connected interaction graph into a tree structure, reducing the number of edges from $\mathcal{O}(N^2)$ to $\mathcal{O}(N)$. Their approach demonstrates that long-range interactions can be approximated efficiently without sacrificing accuracy. Our sparse attention analysis (Theorem 4) provides a theoretical counterpart, bounding the truncation error in terms of the number of neighbors $k$.

3.4 Transformer Universal Approximation

Recent work by Gu et al. (2026) establishes that transformers inherit the universal approximation capability of ReLU networks, and that the number of linear regions—a measure of expressivity—grows exponentially with depth. This provides a theoretical foundation for our approximation rate analysis (Theorem 5).

