4. Graph Transformer Neural Integrator (GraphTNI) Architecture

We now define the GraphTNI architecture, designed to approximate the flow map $\Phi_h$ while respecting the symmetries of the N-body problem.

4.1 Permutation Equivariance

The N-body system is invariant under permutation of particle labels: if $\pi$ is a permutation of $\{1, \dots, N\}$, then the dynamics of the permuted state are identical. Any learned surrogate should respect this symmetry. Standard transformers break permutation invariance due to positional encodings; we enforce it explicitly.

4.2 Equivariant Token Embedding

Definition 1 (Token Embedding). For the $i$-th particle, the initial token embedding is

\mathbf{e}_i^{(0)} = \phi_{\text{node}}(\mathbf{q}_i, \mathbf{p}_i) + \sum_{j \neq i} \psi_{\text{edge}}(\mathbf{q}_i - \mathbf{q}_j, \mathbf{p}_i - \mathbf{p}_j), \tag{4}

where $\phi_{\text{node}}: \mathbb{R}^6 \to \mathbb{R}^{d_{\text{model}}}$ and $\psi_{\text{edge}}: \mathbb{R}^6 \to \mathbb{R}^{d_{\text{model}}}$ are learnable multi-layer perceptrons (MLPs). The use of relative coordinates $\mathbf{q}_i - \mathbf{q}_j$ ensures translation invariance, and the summation over $j$ ensures permutation equivariance.

4.3 Transformer Layers

Definition 2 (Transformer Block). The token embeddings are processed by $L$ decoder layers, each consisting of:

1. Causal Multi-Head Self-Attention: For token $i$, the attention output is
   \mathbf{a}_i^{(l)} = \sum_{j=1}^N \alpha_{ij}^{(l)} \mathbf{V}_j^{(l)}, \quad \alpha_{ij}^{(l)} = \text{softmax}_j\left( \frac{\langle \mathbf{Q}_i^{(l)}, \mathbf{K}_j^{(l)} \rangle}{\sqrt{d_k}} \right),
   with causal masking ensuring $\alpha_{ij} = 0$ for $j > i$ along the time dimension.
2. Feed-Forward Network (FFN): A position-wise MLP applied to each token independently.
3. Residual Connections and Layer Normalization.

The output of the final layer is a sequence of token embeddings $\mathbf{h}_i^{(L)} \in \mathbb{R}^{d_{\text{model}}}$ for $i = 1, \dots, N$.

4.4 Equivariant Readout

Definition 3 (Readout). To predict the state increment for particle $i$, we use a permutation-invariant aggregation:

\Delta \hat{\mathbf{x}}_i = \rho\!\left( \mathbf{h}_i^{(L)}, \sum_{j \neq i} \gamma(\mathbf{h}_i^{(L)}, \mathbf{h}_j^{(L)}) \right), \tag{5}

where $\rho: \mathbb{R}^{d_{\text{model}} \times d_{\text{model}}} \to \mathbb{R}^6$ and $\gamma: \mathbb{R}^{d_{\text{model}} \times d_{\text{model}}} \to \mathbb{R}^{d_{\text{model}}}$ are MLPs. The final predicted state is

\hat{\mathbf{x}}_{t+1, i} = \mathbf{x}_{t,i} + \Delta \hat{\mathbf{x}}_i. \tag{6}

The residual formulation encourages the model to learn the small increment $\Delta \mathbf{x} = \Phi_h(\mathbf{x}_t) - \mathbf{x}_t$, which is numerically advantageous.

4.5 Autoregressive Flow Approximation

Given a context window of $K$ consecutive states $X_t = (\mathbf{x}_{t-K+1}, \dots, \mathbf{x}_t)$, GraphTNI predicts the state at $t+1$:

\hat{\mathbf{x}}_{t+1} = \text{GraphTNI}_\theta(\mathbf{x}_{t-K+1}, \dots, \mathbf{x}_t). \tag{7}

Heuristic 1 (Context Window Length). The exact flow $\Phi_h$ is Markovian ($\mathbf{x}_{t+1}$ depends only on $\mathbf{x}_t$). However, training data from a symplectic integrator of order $p$ has truncation error depending on derivatives up to order $p+1$. A context window $K \ge p+1$ allows the transformer to implicitly estimate these derivatives, reducing the irreducible approximation error. We conjecture that $K = p+1$ is sufficient.

