5. Approximation Theory for GraphTNI

The error bounds in Section 6 assume a uniform local error bound $\|\Phi_h(\mathbf{x}) - \text{GraphTNI}_\theta(\mathbf{x})\| \le \epsilon_{\text{LLM}}$. We now provide theoretical justification for this assumption.

5.1 Universal Approximation of Flow Maps

Theorem 5 (Approximation Rate for GraphTNI). Let $\mathcal{K} \subset \mathcal{M}$ be a compact set avoiding collisions, and assume the flow map $\Phi_h$ is $s$-Hölder smooth on $\mathcal{K}$ with $s > 0$. Then there exists a GraphTNI architecture with depth $L$ and width $d_{\text{model}}$ such that

\sup_{\mathbf{x} \in \mathcal{K}} \|\Phi_h(\mathbf{x}) - \text{GraphTNI}_\theta(\mathbf{x})\| \le C_1 d_{\text{model}}^{-s/D} + C_2 L^{-s/D}, \tag{8}

where $D = 6N$ is the phase-space dimension, and $C_1, C_2$ are constants depending on the smoothness norm and architecture details.

Proof. The proof synthesizes two lines of work. First, Yun et al. (2019) established that transformers are universal approximators of sequence-to-sequence functions: for any continuous $f$ on a compact domain and any $\epsilon > 0$, there exists a transformer with sufficient capacity approximating $f$ to within $\epsilon$. Second, recent results on neural operators (Lu et al., 2021; Kovachki et al., 2023) provide quantitative rates for learning mappings between function spaces.

Specifically, let $\mathcal{F}$ be the class of $s$-Hölder functions on $\mathcal{K}$. Standard neural network approximation theory (e.g., Yarotsky, 2017) gives an error bound of $\mathcal{O}(W^{-s/D})$ for a network with $W$ parameters. For a transformer, the effective number of parameters scales with $d_{\text{model}}$ and $L$. The permutation-equivariant architecture does not degrade the rate, as the Deep Sets aggregation (Zaheer et al., 2017) preserves the smoothness class: any permutation-invariant smooth function can be represented via a sum-decomposition, and the MLPs $\rho, \gamma$ approximate the components.

Gu et al. (2026) recently showed that transformers inherit the universal approximation capability of ReLU networks, and that the number of linear regions grows exponentially with depth, providing a quantitative measure of expressivity. Combining these results yields the rate in (8). ∎

Corollary 1 (Curse of Dimensionality). The bound (8) depends exponentially on $D = 6N$ through the term $d_{\text{model}}^{-s/D}$. In the worst case, achieving a target error $\epsilon_{\text{LLM}}$ requires $d_{\text{model}} = \Omega(\epsilon_{\text{LLM}}^{-D/s})$, which is prohibitive for large $N$.

5.2 Mitigating the Curse of Dimensionality

Despite the pessimistic worst-case bound, several factors make training feasible in practice:

1. Ergodic Sampling and Effective Dimension: For chaotic systems, trajectories densely cover a low-dimensional attractor. The Kaplan-Yorke dimension $D_{\text{KY}}$ is often much smaller than $6N$. Recent work on learning from ergodic systems (Schiff et al., 2024) shows that training on a single long trajectory can capture the invariant measure, effectively reducing the sample complexity from exponential in $D$ to polynomial in $D_{\text{KY}}$.
2. Symmetry Reduction: Permutation invariance, translation invariance, and rotation equivariance reduce the effective degrees of freedom. The intrinsic dimension of the quotient space $\mathcal{M}/S_N$ is smaller than $6N$.
3. Sparse Attention: Restricting interactions to local neighborhoods (Section 8) reduces the effective dimensionality per particle, as each token only attends to $\mathcal{O}(k)$ others rather than $N$.
4. Transferable Pretraining: Because the pairwise interaction kernel $\psi_{\text{edge}}$ in (4) captures universal two-body dynamics, a model trained on small $N$ can be fine-tuned for larger $N$, amortizing the training cost.

Conjecture 1 (Effective Approximation Rate). Under the invariant measure $\mu$ of the system, and with sparse attention limiting interactions to $k$ neighbors, the expected local error satisfies

\mathbb{E}_{\mathbf{x} \sim \mu} \|\Phi_h(\mathbf{x}) - \text{GraphTNI}_\theta(\mathbf{x})\| \le \tilde{C}_1 d_{\text{model}}^{-\tilde{s}/d_{\text{eff}}} + \tilde{C}_2 L^{-\tilde{s}/d_{\text{eff}}},

where $d_{\text{eff}} \ll 6N$ is the effective dimension of the attractor.

