6. The Hybrid Predictor-Corrector Framework

Direct autoregressive rollout of GraphTNI suffers from compounding error, as governed by Theorem 1. We now introduce a hybrid scheme that periodically corrects the surrogate with a trusted reference integrator, and prove a global error bound.

6.1 Algorithm Definition

Algorithm 1: Hybrid GraphTNI-Augmented Evolution
Input: Initial state $\mathbf{x}_0$, context length $K$, correction interval $C \in \mathbb{N}^+$.
Output: Sequence of states $\mathbf{x}_t$ for $t = 0, 1, \dots$

1: $t \leftarrow 0$
2: while $t < T_{\text{max}}$ do
3: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; for $j = 1$ to $C$ do
4: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; $\mathbf{x}_{t+j} \leftarrow \text{GraphTNI}_\theta(\mathbf{x}_{t+j-K}, \dots, \mathbf{x}_{t+j-1})$
5: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; end for
6: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; $\mathbf{x}_{t+C} \leftarrow \Phi_h^{\text{ref}}(\mathbf{x}_{t+C-1})$
7: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; $t \leftarrow t + C$
8: end while

The reference integrator $\Phi_h^{\text{ref}}$ is assumed to be a high-fidelity symplectic solver (e.g., 8th-order Gauss-Legendre). The correction step resets the accumulated surrogate error.

6.2 Assumptions for the Error Bound

We work in the Euclidean norm $\|\cdot\|$ on $\mathbb{R}^{6N}$. Let $\mathcal{K} \subset \mathcal{M}$ be a compact forward-invariant set containing the trajectory of interest.

Assumption 1 (Local Surrogate Error). There exists $\epsilon_{\text{LLM}} > 0$ such that for all $\mathbf{x} \in \mathcal{K}$,

\|\Phi_h(\mathbf{x}) - \text{GraphTNI}_\theta(\mathbf{x})\| \le \epsilon_{\text{LLM}}. \tag{9}

Assumption 2 (Reference Integrator Error). The reference integrator $\Phi_h^{\text{ref}}$ has local error bounded by $\epsilon_{\text{ref}}$ on $\mathcal{K}$:

\|\Phi_h(\mathbf{x}) - \Phi_h^{\text{ref}}(\mathbf{x})\| \le \epsilon_{\text{ref}}. \tag{10}

Assumption 3 (Lipschitz Flow). The exact flow is Lipschitz on $\mathcal{K}$ with constant $e^{L h}$:

\|\Phi_h(\mathbf{x}) - \Phi_h(\mathbf{y})\| \le e^{L h} \|\mathbf{x} - \mathbf{y}\|, \quad \forall \mathbf{x}, \mathbf{y} \in \mathcal{K}. \tag{11}

Assumption 4 (Error Hierarchy). $\epsilon_{\text{ref}} \ll \epsilon_{\text{LLM}}$.

6.3 Global Error Bound

Theorem 2 (Global Error Bound for Hybrid Correction). Under Assumptions 1–4, for any initial state $\mathbf{x}_0 \in \mathcal{K}$ and number of correction cycles $M$ such that the trajectory remains in $\mathcal{K}$, the global error satisfies

\|\mathbf{x}_{M \cdot C} - \Phi_{M C h}(\mathbf{x}_0)\| \le \left( \epsilon_{\text{LLM}} \frac{e^{L C h} - 1}{e^{L h} - 1} \right) \frac{e^{L M C h} - 1}{e^{L C h} - 1} + \mathcal{O}(\epsilon_{\text{ref}}). \tag{12}

Proof. Let $\mathbf{y}_0 \in \mathcal{K}$ be an exact state (i.e., $\mathbf{y}_0 = \Phi_{t}(\mathbf{x}_0)$ for some $t$). Consider one block of $C$ GraphTNI steps starting from $\mathbf{y}_0$. Define

\mathbf{y}_k = \text{GraphTNI}_\theta^k(\mathbf{y}_0), \quad \mathbf{z}_k = \Phi_{k h}(\mathbf{y}_0),

and let $E_k = \|\mathbf{y}_k - \mathbf{z}_k\|$. For $k = 1$, by (9), $E_1 \le \epsilon_{\text{LLM}}$. For $k \ge 2$, we use the decomposition

\|\mathbf{y}_k - \mathbf{z}_k\| \le \|\text{GraphTNI}_\theta(\mathbf{y}_{k-1}) - \Phi_h(\mathbf{y}_{k-1})\| + \|\Phi_h(\mathbf{y}_{k-1}) - \Phi_h(\mathbf{z}_{k-1})\|.

The first term is bounded by $\epsilon_{\text{LLM}}$ (by (9)), and the second by $e^{L h} E_{k-1}$ (by (11)). Hence

E_k \le \epsilon_{\text{LLM}} + e^{L h} E_{k-1}.

This is a linear recurrence. Unrolling:

E_C \le \epsilon_{\text{LLM}} \sum_{j=0}^{C-1} e^{j L h} = \epsilon_{\text{LLM}} \frac{e^{L C h} - 1}{e^{L h} - 1}. \tag{13}

Now apply the reference correction at step $C$. Let $\tilde{\mathbf{y}}_C = \Phi_h^{\text{ref}}(\mathbf{y}_{C-1})$. The error after correction is

\|\tilde{\mathbf{y}}_C - \mathbf{z}_C\| \le \|\Phi_h^{\text{ref}}(\mathbf{y}_{C-1}) - \Phi_h(\mathbf{y}_{C-1})\| + \|\Phi_h(\mathbf{y}_{C-1}) - \Phi_h(\mathbf{z}_{C-1})\| \le \epsilon_{\text{ref}} + e^{L h} E_{C-1}.

Since $E_{C-1} \le E_C$, we define the reset error

E_{\text{reset}} = \epsilon_{\text{ref}} + e^{L h} E_C. \tag{14}

Now consider the macro-evolution over $M$ correction cycles. Let $\mathbf{x}_m^* = \mathbf{x}_{m \cdot C}$ be the state after $m$ cycles, and $\mathbf{z}_m^* = \Phi_{m C h}(\mathbf{x}_0)$ the exact state. The evolution from $\mathbf{x}_{m-1}^*$ to $\mathbf{x}_m^*$ consists of $C$ GraphTNI steps followed by one reference step, which we have shown introduces an error of at most $E_{\text{reset}}$ relative to the exact flow over $C h$. Therefore, by the same Lipschitz argument applied at the macro-scale,

\|\mathbf{x}_m^* - \mathbf{z}_m^*\| \le E_{\text{reset}} + e^{L C h} \|\mathbf{x}_{m-1}^* - \mathbf{z}_{m-1}^*\|.

Unrolling this recurrence over $M$ cycles yields

\|\mathbf{x}_M^* - \mathbf{z}_M^*\| \le E_{\text{reset}} \sum_{j=0}^{M-1} e^{j L C h} = E_{\text{reset}} \frac{e^{L M C h} - 1}{e^{L C h} - 1}. \tag{15}

Substituting $E_{\text{reset}} = \epsilon_{\text{ref}} + e^{L h} E_C$ and the bound (13) for $E_C$ gives

\|\mathbf{x}_M^* - \mathbf{z}_M^*\| \le \left( \epsilon_{\text{LLM}} \frac{e^{L C h} - 1}{e^{L h} - 1} \right) \frac{e^{L M C h} - 1}{e^{L C h} - 1} + \epsilon_{\text{ref}} \frac{e^{L M C h} - 1}{e^{L C h} - 1}.

Since $\epsilon_{\text{ref}} \ll \epsilon_{\text{LLM}}$, the second term is $\mathcal{O}(\epsilon_{\text{ref}})$, completing the proof. ∎

Corollary 2 (Error Reset Property). The error doubling time in the hybrid scheme is $t_{\text{double}} = (\ln 2) / (L C h)$, which is $C$ times larger than the doubling time $(\ln 2) / (L h)$ of pure GraphTNI rollout.

Corollary 3 (Optimal Correction Interval). Balancing computational cost (larger $C$ reduces reference evaluations) against accuracy (larger $C$ increases per-cycle error) yields the optimal fixed correction interval

C_{\text{opt}} = \left\lfloor \frac{1}{L h} \ln\!\left( \frac{\epsilon_{\text{ref}}}{\epsilon_{\text{LLM}}} (e^{L h} - 1) + 1 \right) \right\rfloor. \tag{16}

Physical Interpretation. If we approximate $L \approx \lambda_{\max}$ and choose $C h = 0.1 t_\lambda$, then from (13), $E_C \approx \epsilon_{\text{LLM}} e^{0.1} \approx 1.1 \epsilon_{\text{LLM}}$. Thus, synchronizing every 10% of the Lyapunov time keeps the per-cycle error nearly constant, preventing exponential blow-up.

Remark 2 (Geometric Interpretation). Algorithm 1 can be viewed as a composition method $\Psi_{C h} = \Phi_h^{\text{ref}} \circ \text{GraphTNI}_\theta^{C-1}$. Unlike standard symplectic composition methods (e.g., Yoshida splittings), our scheme allows a non-symplectic inner map. Theorem 2 shows that global error is controlled provided $C$ satisfies (16), generalizing composition methods to non-symplectic surrogates.

