2. Higher-Order Composition: Extend Algorithm 1 to use higher-order composition methods (e.g., Yoshida splittings) to improve the effective order of the hybrid scheme.
3. Scaling to Cosmological $N$: For $N \sim 10^9$, combine sparse GraphTNI with Particle-Mesh methods. Theorem 2 provides the error-control framework for such multi-scale hybrids.
4. Variational Extensions: Integrate GraphTNI with neural action functionals (NAF) to enforce variational consistency, potentially improving long-term stability beyond what Proposition 1 guarantees.
5. Empirical Validation: While this work is purely theoretical, a natural next step is to validate Theorem 2 and Proposition 1 on standard benchmarks (e.g., Pythagorean three-body, Figure-8 orbit) and compare against HNN and Neural ODE baselines.

