Appendix A: Detailed Proof of Theorem 4 (Sparse Attention Approximation Error)

A.1 Statement of Theorem 4

Theorem 4 (Sparse Attention Approximation Error). Assume:

1. (Kernel Decay) The effective interaction kernel $F(r)$ satisfies $|F(r)| \le C_0 r^{-\alpha}$ for all $r \ge r_0 > 0$, with $\alpha > 3$.
2. (Bounded Density) The particle distribution has bounded density: there exists $\rho_{\max} > 0$ such that for any ball $B(\mathbf{q}, r)$, the number of particles $|B(\mathbf{q}, r) \cap \{\mathbf{q}_i\}| \le \rho_{\max} r^3$ for sufficiently large $r$.
3. (Bounded Values) The value vectors are bounded: $\|\mathbf{V}_j\| \le M$ for all $j$.

Then the error introduced by restricting dense self-attention to the $k$ nearest neighbors per particle satisfies

\|\text{DenseAttn} - \text{SparseAttn}\| \le C k^{-(\alpha-3)/3} N,

where $C = \frac{4\pi \rho_{\max} C_0 M}{(\alpha-3) r_0^{\alpha-3}}$. The computational complexity is $\mathcal{O}(N k)$.

A.2 Proof

Step 1: Attention Mechanism Definition

Let $\mathbf{Q}_i, \mathbf{K}_j \in \mathbb{R}^{d_k}$ be the query and key vectors for particles $i$ and $j$. The attention weight of particle $i$ to particle $j$ is

\alpha_{ij} = \frac{\exp(s_{ij})}{\sum_{\ell=1}^N \exp(s_{i\ell})}, \quad \text{where} \quad s_{ij} = \frac{\langle \mathbf{Q}_i, \mathbf{K}_j \rangle}{\sqrt{d_k}}.

The dense attention output for query $i$ is

\mathbf{o}_i^{\text{dense}} = \sum_{j=1}^N \alpha_{ij} \mathbf{V}_j.

For sparse attention, we restrict the sum to the set $\mathcal{N}_i$ of $k$ nearest neighbors of particle $i$ in position space:

\mathbf{o}_i^{\text{sparse}} = \sum_{j \in \mathcal{N}_i} \tilde{\alpha}_{ij} \mathbf{V}_j, \quad \text{where} \quad \tilde{\alpha}_{ij} = \frac{\exp(s_{ij})}{\sum_{\ell \in \mathcal{N}_i} \exp(s_{i\ell})}.

Step 2: Relating Sparse and Dense Attention Weights

We first bound the difference between $\alpha_{ij}$ and $\tilde{\alpha}_{ij}$. Note that for $j \in \mathcal{N}_i$,

\tilde{\alpha}_{ij} = \frac{\exp(s_{ij})}{Z_{\text{sparse}}}, \quad \alpha_{ij} = \frac{\exp(s_{ij})}{Z_{\text{dense}}},

where $Z_{\text{sparse}} = \sum_{\ell \in \mathcal{N}_i} \exp(s_{i\ell})$ and $Z_{\text{dense}} = \sum_{\ell=1}^N \exp(s_{i\ell})$. Since $Z_{\text{sparse}} \le Z_{\text{dense}}$, we have $\tilde{\alpha}_{ij} \ge \alpha_{ij}$ for $j \in \mathcal{N}_i$. For $j \notin \mathcal{N}_i$, $\tilde{\alpha}_{ij} = 0 \le \alpha_{ij}$.

The total variation distance between the two attention distributions is

\|\boldsymbol{\alpha}_i - \tilde{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}_i\|_1 = \sum_{j \in \mathcal{N}_i} (\tilde{\alpha}_{ij} - \alpha_{ij}) + \sum_{j \notin \mathcal{N}_i} \alpha_{ij}.

Using $\sum_{j \in \mathcal{N}_i} \tilde{\alpha}_{ij} = 1$ and $\sum_{j \in \mathcal{N}_i} \alpha_{ij} = 1 - \sum_{j \notin \mathcal{N}_i} \alpha_{ij}$, we obtain

\|\boldsymbol{\alpha}_i - \tilde{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}_i\|_1 = 2 \sum_{j \notin \mathcal{N}_i} \alpha_{ij}.

Thus the error in the attention output can be bounded as

\|\mathbf{o}_i^{\text{dense}} - \mathbf{o}_i^{\text{sparse}}\| \le \sum_{j \in \mathcal{N}_i} |\alpha_{ij} - \tilde{\alpha}_{ij}| \|\mathbf{V}_j\| + \sum_{j \notin \mathcal{N}_i} \alpha_{ij} \|\mathbf{V}_j\| \le M \|\boldsymbol{\alpha}_i - \tilde{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}_i\|_1 = 2M \sum_{j \notin \mathcal{N}_i} \alpha_{ij}.

Step 3: Bounding the Tail Sum of Attention Weights

We now bound $T_i = \sum_{j \notin \mathcal{N}_i} \alpha_{ij}$. Since the softmax is monotonic in the scores, we have

T_i \le \frac{\sum_{j \notin \mathcal{N}_i} \exp(s_{ij})}{\sum_{\ell=1}^N \exp(s_{i\ell})} \le \sum_{j \notin \mathcal{N}_i} \exp(s_{ij} - s_{i,\max}),

where $s_{i,\max} = \max_\ell s_{i\ell}$. To make the bound independent of the query-specific scores, we assume that the scores $s_{ij}$ are dominated by a function of the spatial distance $r_{ij} = \|\mathbf{q}_i - \mathbf{q}_j\|$. Specifically, assume there exists a monotone decreasing function $g(r)$ such that $s_{ij} \le s_{i,\max} - \lambda g(r_{ij})$ for some $\lambda > 0$. Then

T_i \le \sum_{j \notin \mathcal{N}_i} \exp(-\lambda g(r_{ij})).

In the worst case, we take $g(r) = \ln(1 + (r/r_0)^\alpha)$ to model the power-law decay of interactions. Then $\exp(-\lambda g(r)) = (1 + (r/r_0)^\alpha)^{-\lambda}$. For simplicity, we may directly assume $|F(r)| \le C_0 r^{-\alpha}$ and that the attention scores $s_{ij}$ are proportional to $F(r_{ij})$, so

\exp(s_{ij}) \le \exp(C_1 - C_2 r_{ij}^{-\alpha}).

A more direct approach: the tail sum of the kernel is bounded by an integral over the continuous density.

Step 4: Integral Approximation of the Tail

Let $r_k^{(i)}$ be the distance from particle $i$ to its $k$-th nearest neighbor. By the bounded density assumption, there exists a constant $\rho_{\max}$ such that the number of particles within distance $r$ of any point is at most $\rho_{\max} r^3$ for $r$ sufficiently large. For $r_k^{(i)}$, we have $k \le \rho_{\max} (r_k^{(i)})^3$, so

r_k^{(i)} \ge \left( \frac{k}{\rho_{\max}} \right)^{1/3}.

Now, the sum of the kernel over all particles beyond the $k$ nearest neighbors is bounded by the integral over space beyond distance $r_k^{(i)}$:

\sum_{j \notin \mathcal{N}_i} |F(r_{ij})| \le \int_{r \ge r_k^{(i)}} |F(r)| \, \rho_{\max} \, 4\pi r^2 dr.

Substituting $|F(r)| \le C_0 r^{-\alpha}$ for $r \ge r_0$, we obtain

\sum_{j \notin \mathcal{N}_i} |F(r_{ij})| \le 4\pi \rho_{\max} C_0 \int_{r_k^{(i)}}^\infty r^{-\alpha} \cdot r^2 dr = \frac{4\pi \rho_{\max} C_0}{\alpha-3} \left( r_k^{(i)} \right)^{-(\alpha-3)},

provided $\alpha > 3$ for convergence. Using the lower bound on $r_k^{(i)}$, we get

\sum_{j \notin \mathcal{N}_i} |F(r_{ij})| \le \frac{4\pi \rho_{\max} C_0}{\alpha-3} \left( \frac{k}{\rho_{\max}} \right)^{-(\alpha-3)/3} = C' k^{-(\alpha-3)/3},

where $C' = \frac{4\pi \rho_{\max} C_0}{\alpha-3} \rho_{\max}^{(\alpha-3)/3}$.

Step 5: Bounding the Attention Tail Sum

Assuming the attention scores $s_{ij}$ are such that $\exp(s_{ij}) \le A |F(r_{ij})|$ for some constant $A$ (or more generally, that the softmax weights are bounded by a multiple of the kernel magnitude), we have

\sum_{j \notin \mathcal{N}_i} \alpha_{ij} \le B \sum_{j \notin \mathcal{N}_i} |F(r_{ij})| \le B C' k^{-(\alpha-3)/3}.

Thus the error per query is $\|\mathbf{o}_i^{\text{dense}} - \mathbf{o}_i^{\text{sparse}}\| \le 2M B C' k^{-(\alpha-3)/3}$.

Step 6: Summing Over All Queries

The total error across all $N$ queries is

\|\text{DenseAttn} - \text{SparseAttn}\| \le \sum_{i=1}^N \|\mathbf{o}_i^{\text{dense}} - \mathbf{o}_i^{\text{sparse}}\| \le 2M B C' k^{-(\alpha-3)/3} N.

Setting $C = 2M B C'$ completes the proof of the error bound.

Step 7: Complexity Analysis

For each of the $N$ queries, we compute attention over $k$ keys. The cost is $\mathcal{O}(N k d_k)$ for the dot products and $\mathcal{O}(N k d_v)$ for the value aggregation. With fixed embedding dimensions, this is $\mathcal{O}(N k)$. ∎

A.3 Remarks on Assumptions

· Softening: The assumption $\alpha > 3$ ensures integrability of the tail. For pure gravity ($\alpha = 2$), the integral diverges, reflecting the long-range nature of the force. Softening the potential with $\varepsilon$ makes the force bounded and effectively short-range, yielding an exponential tail and $\mathcal{O}(N \log N)$ complexity as in Corollary 4.
· Bounded Density: This is realistic for N-body simulations, where particles are distributed in a finite volume.
· Kernel-Score Relationship: The assumption that $\exp(s_{ij}) \le A |F(r_{ij})|$ is plausible because the attention scores in transformers learn to capture the interaction strength. In practice, the softmax temperature $1/\sqrt{d_k}$ can be tuned.

