Appendix D: Lipschitz Constant and Softening Details

D.1 Lipschitz Constant for Softened Gravity

With Plummer softening $\varepsilon > 0$, the gravitational potential between particles $i$ and $j$ is

V_{ij}(\mathbf{q}_i, \mathbf{q}_j) = - \frac{G m_i m_j}{\sqrt{\|\mathbf{q}_i - \mathbf{q}_j\|^2 + \varepsilon^2}}.

The force on particle $i$ due to particle $j$ is

\mathbf{F}_{ij} = -\nabla_{\mathbf{q}_i} V_{ij} = - \frac{G m_i m_j (\mathbf{q}_i - \mathbf{q}_j)}{(\|\mathbf{q}_i - \mathbf{q}_j\|^2 + \varepsilon^2)^{3/2}}.

The Jacobian of the force with respect to positions is

\frac{\partial \mathbf{F}_{ij}}{\partial \mathbf{q}_i} = - \frac{G m_i m_j}{(\|\mathbf{q}_i - \mathbf{q}_j\|^2 + \varepsilon^2)^{5/2}} \left[ (\|\mathbf{q}_i - \mathbf{q}_j\|^2 + \varepsilon^2) I - 3 (\mathbf{q}_i - \mathbf{q}_j)(\mathbf{q}_i - \mathbf{q}_j)^T \right].

The spectral norm of this matrix is bounded by

\left\| \frac{\partial \mathbf{F}_{ij}}{\partial \mathbf{q}_i} \right\| \le \frac{G m_i m_j}{(\|\mathbf{q}_i - \mathbf{q}_j\|^2 + \varepsilon^2)^{3/2}} \cdot 2 \le \frac{2 G m_i m_j}{\varepsilon^3}.

Summing over all $j \neq i$, the Lipschitz constant of the total force on particle $i$ is bounded by

L_i^{\text{force}} \le \sum_{j \neq i} \frac{2 G m_i m_j}{\varepsilon^3}.

The full vector field $f(\mathbf{x}) = (\dot{\mathbf{q}}, \dot{\mathbf{p}})$ has components $\dot{\mathbf{q}}_i = \mathbf{p}_i/m_i$ and $\dot{\mathbf{p}}_i = \sum_{j \neq i} \mathbf{F}_{ij}$. The Lipschitz constant $L$ of $f$ satisfies

L \le \max_i \left( \frac{1}{m_i} + \sum_{j \neq i} \frac{2 G m_j}{\varepsilon^3} \right). \tag{D.1}

This bound is finite and independent of the particle separations, ensuring that Assumption 3 of Theorem 2 holds uniformly on any domain with softening $\varepsilon$.

D.2 Softening Error

Softening introduces a bias in the dynamics. The error in the potential is $\mathcal{O}(\varepsilon^2 / r^3)$ for $r \gg \varepsilon$. By choosing $\varepsilon$ appropriately (e.g., $\varepsilon \sim 10^{-3}$ in normalized units), one can balance accuracy and computational stability.

