Appendix E: Architecture and Training Specifications

E.1 GraphTNI Architecture Details

Token Embedding (Eq. (4)):

· $\phi_{\text{node}}$: MLP with 2 hidden layers of size $4 \times d_{\text{model}}$, ReLU activation.
· $\psi_{\text{edge}}$: MLP with 2 hidden layers of size $4 \times d_{\text{model}}$, ReLU activation.
· Output dimension: $d_{\text{model}} = 512$ (default).

Transformer Layers:

· Number of layers $L = 12$.
· Multi-head attention with $h = 8$ heads, $d_k = d_v = d_{\text{model}}/h = 64$.
· Feed-forward network: 2-layer MLP with hidden size $4 \times d_{\text{model}} = 2048$, ReLU activation.
· Layer normalization and residual connections.

Readout (Eqs. (5)-(6)):

· $\gamma$: MLP with 2 hidden layers of size $256$, ReLU.
· $\rho$: MLP with 2 hidden layers of size $256$, ReLU, output dimension $6$ (positions and momenta increments).

Total Parameters: For $N$ up to 100, the model has approximately 50–100 million parameters.

E.2 Training Procedure

Data Generation:

· Use an 8th-order Gauss-Legendre symplectic integrator (GL8) with timestep $h = 0.01$ (in units where $G=1$, typical orbital timescale $\sim 1$).
· Generate $10^5$ trajectories of length $1000$ steps for $N=3$ to $N=10$ systems, sampling initial conditions from virialized Plummer spheres.
· Apply random rotations and translations to augment the dataset.

Loss Function:

· Mean Squared Error (MSE) on the predicted state increment:

\mathcal{L}(\theta) = \frac{1}{|\mathcal{B}|} \sum_{\mathbf{x} \in \mathcal{B}} \frac{1}{N} \sum_{i=1}^N \|\Delta \hat{\mathbf{x}}_i - \Delta \mathbf{x}_i\|^2,

where $\Delta \mathbf{x}_i = \Phi_h(\mathbf{x})_i - \mathbf{x}_i$ is the true increment.

Optimization:

· Optimizer: AdamW with learning rate $3 \times 10^{-4}$, weight decay $10^{-4}$.
· Batch size: 256 sequences of length $K=10$.
· Training for 500,000 steps (approximately 3 days on 8× A100 GPUs).

E.3 Sparse Attention Implementation

For sparse attention, we use a kd-tree to find the $k$ nearest neighbors for each particle. The attention mask is recomputed every $10$ steps to account for particle motion. The complexity is $\mathcal{O}(N k)$ per forward pass.

E.4 Hybrid Correction Implementation

· Reference integrator $\Phi_h^{\text{ref}}$: GL8 with the same timestep $h$.
· Correction interval $C$: chosen adaptively based on local Lipschitz estimate $L(\mathbf{x}) \propto \max_{i,j} \|\mathbf{q}_i - \mathbf{q}_j\|^{-3}$ (with softening). A simple heuristic: $C = \lfloor C_{\text{base}} \cdot (r_{\min}/\varepsilon)^3 \rfloor$, clipped to $[1, C_{\max}]$.

