Appendix F: Additional Theoretical Considerations

F.1 Validity of the Lipschitz Assumption

The Lipschitz constant $L$ in Theorem 2 is assumed uniform on $\mathcal{K}$. In practice, $L$ varies across phase space. Our error bound can be generalized to a non-uniform Lipschitz setting by replacing $L$ with its maximum over the trajectory segment. For adaptive correction, a state-dependent $C(\mathbf{x})$ as proposed in Section 6.3 provides a practical solution.

F.2 Probabilistic Error Bounds

Conjecture 2 suggests a probabilistic error bound under the invariant measure. A possible proof strategy: use results from statistical learning theory (e.g., Rademacher complexity) to bound the generalization error of GraphTNI. Since the invariant measure is often supported on a low-dimensional attractor, the effective sample complexity may be much smaller than the ambient dimension.

F.3 Connection to Reinforcement Learning

The optimal correction interval $C_{\text{opt}}$ in Eq. (16) depends on the local Lipschitz constant $L$. Learning a policy $C(\mathbf{x})$ via reinforcement learning, as in Saz Ulibarrena and Portegies Zwart (2025), can be viewed as approximating this optimal state-dependent correction. Our Theorem 2 provides the theoretical reward function: minimize computational cost subject to an error tolerance derived from the bound.

F.4 Generalization to Other Hamiltonian Systems

While this work focuses on the gravitational N-body problem, the framework extends to any Hamiltonian system with a smooth vector field. The key requirements are:

· A symplectic reference integrator.
· A compact forward-invariant set $\mathcal{K}$ where training data is generated.
· A permutation-equivariant or appropriate symmetry-respecting architecture.

Applications include molecular dynamics, plasma physics, and celestial mechanics.


